<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Home on Zig SHOWTIME</title><link>https://zig.show/</link><description>Recent content in Home on Zig SHOWTIME</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 19:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://zig.show/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Rewriting Roc</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/38/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 19:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/38/</guid><description>&lt;p>As the techyap-sphere &lt;a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42935516">has discovered&lt;/a> a couple days ago, &lt;a href="https://roc-lang.org">the Roc programming language&lt;/a> has decided to rewrite the Roc compiler from Rust to Zig.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Roc is no stranger to Zig as that&amp;rsquo;s the language in which Roc&amp;rsquo;s standard library was already implemented in, but until very recently it proudly sported a &amp;ldquo;double citizenship&amp;rdquo;: Rust in the sheets (the compiler), Zig in the streets (the stdlib).&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;a href="https://gist.github.com/rtfeldman/77fb430ee57b42f5f2ca973a3992532f">Now things have changed&lt;/a>, and this has immediately spawned a storm of discussions about the merits of one language versus the other. In this episode we&amp;rsquo;re not interested in the memory safety wars, but rather in the much more interesting aspect of how a project that started with Rust, and which over time attracted compiler engineers who are proficient in Rust, ended up successfully building both the confidence and the consensus required to switch to Zig.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Microscope</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/37/</link><pubDate>Fri, 31 Jan 2025 15:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/37/</guid><description>&lt;p>It&amp;rsquo;s written with a greek mu letter (uscope) but my font doesn&amp;rsquo;t support it, sorry Jim!&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Announcement blog post: &lt;a href="https://www.calabro.io/uscope">https://www.calabro.io/uscope&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Source code: &lt;a href="https://github.com/jcalabro/uscope">https://github.com/jcalabro/uscope&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Zig</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/36/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jan 2024 11:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/36/</guid><description/></item><item><title>dt</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/35/</link><pubDate>Thu, 26 Oct 2023 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/35/</guid><description>&lt;p>dt is a utility and functional-concatenative programming language.&lt;br>
It provides some new ways of scripting and gluing programs together in Unix-like systems like Mac OSX, Linux, and BSD.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;a href="https://github.com/so-dang-cool/dt">https://github.com/so-dang-cool/dt&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Pixi</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/34/</link><pubDate>Mon, 02 Oct 2023 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/34/</guid><description>&lt;p>A nice GUI program, written in Zig, that helps you create art, what&amp;rsquo;s not to love?&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;a href="https://github.com/foxnne/pixi">https://github.com/foxnne/pixi&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Buzz</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/33/</link><pubDate>Thu, 21 Sep 2023 21:30:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/33/</guid><description>&lt;p>Buzz is a lightweight language written in Zig that
compiles to bytecode and runs in a JITted VM.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>You can learn more on the official website:&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;a href="https://buzz-lang.dev/">https://buzz-lang.dev/&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Ghostty</title><link>https://zig.show/episodes/32/</link><pubDate>Tue, 12 Sep 2023 11:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/episodes/32/</guid><description>&lt;p>Mitchell probably doesn&amp;rsquo;t need any introduction, but when it comes specifically to the Zig community he also has has plenty of interesting content he&amp;rsquo;s published on his personal blog:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://mitchellh.com/zig/">Posts on Zig Internals&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>While Ghostty, the subject of his talk, is not openly available yet, he also wrote a few devlogs about it:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://mitchellh.com/ghostty/">Ghostty Devlogs&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul></description></item><item><title/><link>https://zig.show/newsletter/confirm/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zig.show/newsletter/confirm/</guid><description>&lt;div id="next">
